   =20
      SPACman
   =20
 =20
Oh man, speaking of people wrapping their whole identities up in their stoc=
ks and developing unhealthy parasocial relationships with their CEOs, here =
is a=C2=A0wild=C2=A0article about people who threw away all of their money =
on Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s special purpose acquisition company,  Pershing Squ=
are Tontine Holdings, for no particular reason. For instance,=C2=A0this =E2=
=80=9Ca 39-year-old software engineer who had saved $1.6 million over 20 ye=
ars =E2=80=94 ever since he began working at the age of 18=E2=80=9D:Until 2=
020, he had socked all of it away in a Chase savings account because, he sa=
ys, =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t trust the stock market.=E2=80=9D ...Last year=
, the software engineer =E2=80=94 who works as an independent consultant =
=E2=80=94 finally decided to take the plunge and put his money into the sto=
ck market, setting up an account at Fidelity. ...By last fall, friends were=
 talking up Ackman=E2=80=99s SPAC. The software engineer decided it was the=
 only stock he would buy, sinking the entire $1.6 million into it.=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9CAckman just sounded very confident. I trusted the guy. I thought he k=
new what he was doing,=E2=80=9D he says.At first, the software engineer bou=
ght common stock, but later, he says, =E2=80=9Clike an amateur=E2=80=9D he =
transferred shares into expensive, in-the-money call options with a strike =
price of $22 =E2=80=94 well below the $30 where the stock was trading at th=
e time. =E2=80=9CI thought it was safe,=E2=80=9D he says.The highest his ac=
count=E2=80=99s value ever reached was $2 million, but had those options wo=
rked out, he calculates he would have made almost $4 million.They expired w=
orthless on July 16, a few days before Ackman announced the SEC had torpedo=
ed his plans.=E2=80=9CEverything is my fault,=E2=80=9D the software enginee=
r says. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not Bill=E2=80=99s fault.=E2=80=9DI mean, tru=
e? Bill Ackman didn=E2=80=99t tell you to put your whole life savings into=
=C2=A0call options on his SPAC. (In fact, he specifically told people not t=
o: =E2=80=9CWhat we don=E2=80=99t want people doing is speculating, buying =
short-dated options on our SPAC,=E2=80=9D he said at a public event before =
announcing a deal.) I suppose that the stock market has always provided opp=
ortunities for compulsive gamblers, but it does feel like those opportuniti=
es are heightened these days.=C2=A0
