   =20
      Ryan Cohen
   =20
 =20
Oh man, speaking of people wrapping their whole identities up in their stoc=
ks and developing unhealthy parasocial relationships with their, uh, chairm=
an of the board in this case:Ryan Cohen rose to become chairman of GameStop=
 Corp. with the verve of an old-school corporate raider. Wielding little mo=
re than a minority stake and a sharp tongue, Mr. Cohen pushed out GameStop=
=E2=80=99s executive team and installed longtime associates on the company=
=E2=80=99s board. The tactics made the co-founder of online pet store Chewy=
 Inc. a favorite of the individual investors who sent GameStop=E2=80=99s st=
ock on a roller-coaster this year; they call him =E2=80=9CPapa Cohen.=E2=80=
=9DIf Mr. Cohen has made winning look easy thus far, it is far from clear w=
hat comes next. From his perch as chairman, he has to revamp GameStop=E2=80=
=99s business, if only to justify the stock=E2=80=99s remarkable run. The s=
tock closed Wednesday around $159 per share, up more than eightfold this ye=
ar, but far below the high of $483 it touched in January. The company has r=
eported annual losses for three consecutive years. =E2=80=A6Mr. Cohen=E2=80=
=99s swift accumulation of power at GameStop, orchestrated from his Florida=
 beachfront apartment located halfway across the country from company headq=
uarters, was the result of a series of previously unreported moves, people =
familiar with the matter said. Fueled in part by his popularity on social m=
edia, Mr. Cohen injected himself into company decision making, all but supp=
lanting the CEO. Board members and executives who were deemed too slow to t=
ransform the company didn=E2=80=99t last long.Mr. Cohen=E2=80=99s takeover =
of GameStop is =E2=80=9Cthe most audacious thing I=E2=80=99ve ever seen,=E2=
=80=9D said Wedbush Securities analyst Michael Pachter. =E2=80=9CHow does a=
 12% shareholder take control of a company?=E2=80=9DI don=E2=80=99t know, I=
 don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s that weird? I feel like activists do this=
 all the time? You get a chunk of shares and you go out to the other shareh=
olders and say =E2=80=9Cthis company is doing a bad job and I would like to=
 install different people to do a better job.=E2=80=9D If the shareholders =
agree with you, you =E2=80=9Ctake over the company=E2=80=9D in some loose s=
ense. (Not an actual acquisition, but you get your people on the board, you=
 replace the executives, the company tries to do your plan, etc.) I don=E2=
=80=99t think it was particularly hard to make the case that a mall-based v=
ideo game retailer had problems, and Cohen=E2=80=99s prior success in onlin=
e commerce made it plausible for him to make the case that he could solve t=
hem.=C2=A0And now he is a meme-stock chairman, =E2=80=9CPapa Cohen,=E2=80=
=9D etc., but I don=E2=80=99t think that his path to power at GameStop reli=
ed all that much on=C2=A0embracing=C2=A0the meme thing. He=E2=80=99s not  A=
dam Aron; he=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t go on Reddit to be like =E2=80=9Cif you vo=
te for my board slate we=E2=80=99re gonna accept Dogecoin at GameStop and m=
ake Harambe our mascot.=E2=80=9D He was just like =E2=80=9Cvideo-game sales=
 are moving online so let=E2=80=99s hire some Amazon executives to make us =
a better competitor in that business.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Just normal reasonable =
stuff you could pitch to a Wall Street analyst.On the other hand! Nothing s=
tops an activist at=C2=A0another=C2=A0company from trying to run the meme-s=
tock playbook. Buy some stock in a struggling company and, instead of going=
 out and pitching your plans to  BlackRock and Vanguard, get on Reddit and =
say like =E2=80=9Cif my board slate is elected we=E2=80=99re gonna take XYZ=
 Co. to the moon and squeeze those short sellers, rocket emoji rocket emoji=
 rocket emoji, not a proxy solicitation, read my SEC filings for full discl=
osures.=E2=80=9D[5] Draw a picture of an ape riding a rocket and slap it on=
 your proxy statement. Call your activist fund Diamond Hands Capital LP.[6]=
 Reddit retail investors can=C2=A0make stocks go up=C2=A0an arbitrary amoun=
t; can they also=C2=A0take over companies?
 =20
   =20
      The Poly hacker
   =20
 =20
We  talked yesterday about how hackers stole about $600 million of cryptocu=
rrency from a decentralized finance protocol called Poly Network, and then =
changed their mind and decided to give back the money. Or some of it. So fa=
r they have given back about $342 million. =E2=80=9CSmart play,=E2=80=9D so=
meone said on Twitter;=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cstealing $600mm and returning $595mm m=
ake you look altruistic while just stealing $5mm makes you look like a jerk=
.=E2=80=9DExactly why the hackers decided to give back (some of?) the money=
 is unclear. There is an argument that security researchers did a good enou=
gh job of identifying them=C2=A0that they=E2=80=99d have a hard time spendi=
ng the stolen money and might get caught by law enforcement, so giving it b=
ack was the safest course. There is an argument that they are just nice? He=
re, however, is the hackers=E2=80=99=C2=A0own explanation, in the form of a=
 Q&A embedded in Ethereum transactions and tweeted by Tom Robinson of block=
chain firm=C2=A0Elliptic:Q: WHY HACKING?A: FOR FUN :)Q: WHY POLY NETWORKA: =
CROSS CHAIN HACKING IS HOTQ: WHY TRANSFERING TOKENS?A: TO KEEP IT SAFE.WHEN=
 SPOTTING THE BUG, I HAD A MIXED FEELING. ASK YOURSELF WHAT TO DO HAD YOU F=
ACING SO MUCH FORTUNE. ASKING THE PROJECT TEAM POLITELY SO THAT THEY CAN FI=
X IT? ANYONE COULD BE THE TRAITOR GIVEN ONE BILLION! I CAN TRUST NOBODY! TH=
E ONLY SOLUTION I CAN COME UP WITH IS SAYING IT IN A _TRUSTED_ ACCOUNT WHIL=
E KEEPING MYSELF _ANONYMOUS_ AND _SAFE_.Obviously you do not have to believ=
e this. I just want to point out that it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=A6=C2=A0right? Li=
ke let=E2=80=99s say you noticed a bug in a popular crypto network that all=
ows anyone to transfer all the money in the network to themselves. What wou=
ld you do? How would you assume that bug got there?If you noticed a bug lik=
e that in the software of a bank, or the Federal Reserve, or Facebook, or w=
hatever, one thing you could do is call up the company=E2=80=99s main numbe=
r and say =E2=80=9CI have found a bug.=E2=80=9D Of course they might ignore=
 you or not understand or not do anything; big institutions are not always =
nimble and clever. But if you managed to get on the phone with=C2=A0Jamie D=
imon and tell him =E2=80=9Chey there=E2=80=99s a bug in your software that =
lets anyone steal a trillion dollars of deposits,=E2=80=9D you would not ex=
pect him to respond =E2=80=9Coh sweet=E2=80=9D and=C2=A0steal the money him=
self.Whereas with a crypto project, if you managed to get on the =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0Discord chat? ... with the =E2=80=A6=C2=A0the stateless pseudonymous =
developer? ... who seems to =E2=80=A6=C2=A0write most of its Medium posts?=
=C2=A0=E2=80=A6 and you said =E2=80=9Chey there=E2=80=99s a bug in your sof=
tware that lets anyone steal a billion dollars of user money,=E2=80=9D and =
he responded =E2=80=9Coh sweet I=E2=80=99m gonna steal it,=E2=80=9D or for =
that matter =E2=80=9Cyes I put it there so that I could steal it and now I =
will,=E2=80=9D you would not be=C2=A0that=C2=A0surprised. I don=E2=80=99t m=
ean to cast any aspersions on Poly Network or anything; I just mean, as a g=
eneral matter, a whole lot of crypto projects really are designed to steal =
all their users=E2=80=99 money.=C2=A0So if you found a bug like this, a tho=
ught process like =E2=80=9CI am going to steal all the money myself so that=
 no one else steals it, and then give it back once the bug is fixed, and ma=
ybe keep a few million dollars=C2=A0for my trouble=E2=80=9D would not be to=
tally unreasonable. I want to be clear that I am=C2=A0very=C2=A0skeptical t=
hat this was actually this hacker=E2=80=99s thought process. I just mean it=
=E2=80=99s a plausible funny thought process.
