</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh wow I had forgotten about <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24724818.264325/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMTEvY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNz=
ZS13b2VzLXNpbmstY2F0YXN0cm9waGUtYm9uZHMtdGllZC10by1iYW5rLXMtcmlza3M/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBd675ba05" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> these bonds</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Credit Suisse Group AG peddled a series of unusual bonds in recent yea=
rs that gave the Swiss firm insurance against the equivalent of a banking e=
arthquake. The owners of those securities are feeling some tremors.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The $461 million of notes, which are rarely traded=
, were quoted at distressed levels last month, with a sliver of the issue s=
elling at around 60 cents on the dollar. Traders at JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co=
. recently offered to buy the junior tranche of the notes for around the sa=
me price, according to two people familiar with matter who asked not to be =
identified as the prices aren=E2=80=99t public.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The bond was quoted at par as recently as March, but doubts have grown=
 over whether the bank=E2=80=99s twin scandals tied to the collapses of Arc=
hegos Capital Management and Greensill Capital might trigger the insurance =
and wipe out the principal of the complex securities.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s turbulent year is turning into a test ca=
se for the unique instruments issued to help reduce the capital the bank ha=
d to set aside to cover operational risk, a broad swath of potential danger=
s from blunders to fraud.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">These bonds <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2472=
4818.264325/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXJ0ZW1pcy5ibS9uZXdzL2NyZWRpdC1zdWlzc2UtZ2V0cy0=
0NjFtLW9wZXJhdGlvbmFsLXJlLWlpaS1vcC1yaXNrLWNhdC1ib25kLWNvdmVyYWdlLw/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB09bad94a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">are great</a>. We have talked about them a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24724818.264325/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTYtMDMtMjUvdW5zaWduZWQtZGVhbHM=
tYW5kLXJvZ3Vpc2gtYm9uZHM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB62c2ed1d" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> couple</a> of <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24724818.264325/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDYtMTQvYmFua3MtZ2V0LWR=
pc3RyYWN0ZWQtYnktdGhlLXdvcmxkLWN1cA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6d496952" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> times</a> ove=
r the years, long before the latest run of Credit Suisse scandals. The basi=
c idea is that there is a category of ways that a bank might lose money tha=
t is called =E2=80=9Coperational risk.=E2=80=9D This is a term that <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24724818.264325/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmlzLm9yZy9saXN0L2JjYnMvdGlkXzI4L2luZGV4Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB227678c4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">comes from bank capital regulation</a>, which <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24724818.264325/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDMtMDUvY2FwaXRhbC1ydWxlcy1nZXQtbGVzcy=
1zdHJlc3NmdWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa21421e0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> requires banks to have enough capit=
al</a> to protect themselves against reasonably likely losses. (That is, th=
ey need to have enough=C2=A0<em>shareholder=C2=A0</em>money to absorb those=
 losses, so that depositors aren=E2=80=99t on the hook.)=C2=A0Bank capital =
regulators say, well, a bank has a certain amount of loans, and some of the=
 loans might go bad, so you need $X billion of capital against the loan boo=
k. And they say, well, the bank has a trading business, and it owns a bunch=
 of stocks and bonds and derivatives, and some of those might go down, so y=
ou need $Y billion of capital against the trading book. And those are the m=
ain normal ways for banks to lose money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bu=
t there are also a whole bunch of other, less normal ways for banks to lose=
 money, ways unrelated to their loans going bad or their trading assets goi=
ng down. Sometimes a teller steals a bunch of money, or the bank pays a hug=
e fine for ripping off clients, or a rogue trader loses money on bad trades=
, or the bank gets hacked. All of this stuff is sort of weird and miscellan=
eous and individually=C2=A0unlikely, but it does <em>happen a lot</em>. And=
 so the regulators say that you need $Z billion of capital against =E2=80=
=9Coperational risk,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0a catch-all term for weird stuff that ca=
n go wrong.[1]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then banks, and particul=
arly Credit Suisse, are very much in the business of optimizing their capit=
al requirements. And one important way to optimize capital requirements is =
by buying insurance. The idea is roughly:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: =
decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">There is some risk that capital regulators think is a big deal.</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s =
a big deal.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can find other peo=
ple, in the market, who don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s a big deal.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you keep the risk, regulators will =
require you to have lots of expensive capital to protect against it.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But if you buy insurance against the r=
isk, they won=E2=80=99t.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The insur=
ance is cheap, because the sellers don=E2=80=99t think the risk is a big de=
al.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s a simple arbitrage: =
It=E2=80=99s cheaper for you to buy third-party insurance against the risk =
(and reduce your capital requirements) than it is for you to self-insure ag=
ainst the risk by having the required capital. The market prices the risk c=
heaper than regulators do, so you insure it in the market.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse loves these trades. For instance, regulators =
require=C2=A0Credit Suisse to have a bunch of capital against the counterpa=
rty credit risk of its derivatives portfolio. (It owns derivatives; if the =
derivatives go up but the people on the other side don=E2=80=99t pay what t=
hey owe, then Credit Suisse will lose money.) This seems like rather a nich=
e risk that you couldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0easily buy insurance against, but Cre=
dit Suisse found an amazing insurer: <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/24724818.264325/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWFsYnJlYWtlci5jb20vMjAxMi8w=
MS9ib251cy13YXRjaA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBaf8cb644" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">its own senior bankers</a>. It =
paid a portion of their bonuses in bonds linked to this credit risk: If the=
 derivatives counterparties=E2=80=99 credit was good, the bankers eventuall=
y got their full bonuses in cash with a nice interest rate; if the counterp=
arties defaulted, the bankers ate the loss. Cool cool cool. This covered on=
ly a=C2=A0portion of the risk, though. Credit Suisse kept the first-loss pi=
ece (as is common in capital-relief trades), the bankers=E2=80=99 bonus poo=
l took the mezzanine piece, and they found another counterparty to take the=
 senior risk. (That trade, too, was amazing, because Credit Suisse ended up=
 sort of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24724818.=
264325/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWFsYnJlYWtlci5jb20vMjAxMi8wNC9tYXJ2ZWwtYXQtdGhlLWRlcml2=
YXRpdmUtb24taXRzLWRlcml2YXRpdmVzLXRoYXQtY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS13cm90ZS10by1pdHN=
lbGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe2c50728" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">writing the insurance to itself</a>.)</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway, another problem for Credit Suisse=E2=80=99=
s fun-loving capital optimizers was operational risk. It fit=C2=A0all of th=
e requirements:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40p=
x; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Bank capital regul=
ators thought that operational risk was a big deal and Credit Suisse needed=
 lots of capital against it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Credi=
t Suisse did not think it was a big deal.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">It could find other people who also didn=E2=80=99t think this risk =
was a big deal.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So it bought insur=
ance, from them, against the risk.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No=
w of course it turns out that the=C2=A0risk was a big deal. That is, always=
, a potential problem with capital-relief trades, and hardly worth talking =
about. Sometimes people=E2=80=99s predictions are off.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">But there is another, subtler, problem with this trade. What ev=
en <em>is=C2=A0</em>this risk? Ordinary capital relief trades are, like, th=
e bank has a bunch of bonds, and it thinks they won=E2=80=99t default, and =
it buys insurance from some counterparty that will pay off if the bonds def=
ault. This allows it to lower its capital requirements. And then if the bon=
ds don=E2=80=99t default, as everyone expects, everyone is happy: The bank =
has successfully lowered its capital requirements (the insurance was cheape=
r than capital would have been), and the counterparty has gotten some free =
money. And if the bonds do default, everyone is sad: The bank probably eats=
 the first loss, and the counterparty has a loss too. But that=E2=80=99s bu=
siness; it happens. And it=E2=80=99s easy to=C2=A0<em>tell=C2=A0</em>if the=
 bonds defaulted.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here, though, =E2=80=9Cop=
erational risk=E2=80=9D is just a random grab bag of things that can go wro=
ng. The shorthand is that=C2=A0operational risk is a sort of residual categ=
ory of =E2=80=9Cevery dumb or criminal thing a bank might get up to,=E2=80=
=9D but you can=E2=80=99t put that shorthand into a bond document. <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24724818.264325/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMTEvY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNz=
ZS13b2VzLXNpbmstY2F0YXN0cm9waGUtYm9uZHMtdGllZC10by1iYW5rLXMtcmlza3M/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cCd675ba05" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> Instead</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>The notes, issued in four parts, were modeled on so-called catastrophe bon=
ds that insure against hurricanes and other natural disasters, and features=
 an intricate structure and a prospectus that runs around 400 pages.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bonds sold in March 2020 -- the third such is=
suance tied to the bank since their debut in 2016 -- are among the world=E2=
=80=99s most complex and secretive, requiring investors to sign non-disclos=
ure agreements, according to people familiar with the deal. They tempted in=
vestors with large coupons and a risk that was marketed as so small it was =
practically unthinkable.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis is p=
robably a textbook case of a catastrophe bond being too complex to price an=
d to market,=E2=80=9D Marcos Alvarez, the head of insurance at DBRS Morning=
star, said in an interview. =E2=80=9CAn insurance company would require fiv=
e or six separate insurance contracts for these perils.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The recent price turmoil has been triggered=
 by confusion over whether Credit Suisse can draw on the insurance for oper=
ational failures, imposing heavy losses to bondholders. The notes cover a h=
uge catalog of risks to the bank=E2=80=99s bottom line, making them almost =
indecipherable even to insurance experts.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">In some loose sense =E2=80=9Coperational risk=E2=80=9D means =
=E2=80=9Cthe bank loses a lot of money quickly by doing dumb things,=E2=80=
=9D and both the Archegos Capital Management situation and the Greensill Ca=
pital situation seem like they might=C2=A0qualify. Archegos <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24724818.264325/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjkvYXJjaGVnb3Mtd2FzLXRv=
by1idXN5LWZvci1tYXJnaW4tY2FsbHM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1d536816" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> resulted in a 165=
-page report</a> by Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s lawyers about how dumb Credit S=
uisse had to be to lose $5.5 billion. With Greensill, Credit Suisse doesn=
=E2=80=99t seem to have lost any money yet, but its clients seem likely to =
lose a lot of money, and absolutely everyone involved is suing everybody el=
se, so=C2=A0there=E2=80=99s a good chance that Credit Suisse will eventuall=
y=C2=A0pay a chunk of money to someone and that you can attribute that mone=
y to, broadly speaking, dumbness and badness.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">But the actual bonds don=E2=80=99t work like that; they have specific ca=
tegories of dumbness and badness that can qualify as an operational-risk lo=
ss, and specific and finicky deductibles and limits for the insurance to ki=
ck in. The bonds define operational risk as =E2=80=9Cthe risk of loss resul=
ting from inadequate or failed internal processes, people and systems or fr=
om external events,=E2=80=9D but not reputational risk, =E2=80=9Closs of bu=
siness opportunities following business interruption,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0credit =
risk or market risk.[2] The definition covers 23 different categories of op=
erational risk, including =E2=80=9Closses resulting from activities/practic=
es (including sales activities, service performance and the appropriateness=
 of products) that either do not comply with regulatory or expected market =
and ethical standards=E2=80=9D (possibly Greensill?) and =E2=80=9Closses du=
e to failures in transaction capture, execution and maintenance relating to=
 transactions and transaction flows of a normal size; scope also covers eve=
nts resulting in market and credit limit breaches=E2=80=9D (possibly Archeg=
os?[3]). And the way the deductibles and limits work, you need multiple eve=
nts in multiple operational-risk categories to actually trigger the bonds.[=
4]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So there is a good chance that the bonds=
 won=E2=80=99t be triggered at all, and that the insurance Credit Suisse pa=
id for will serve its narrow purpose =E2=80=94=C2=A0reducing capital requir=
ements =E2=80=94=C2=A0but not actually pay out anything despite all the bad=
 stuff that Credit Suisse got up to this year. But I guess nobody quite kno=
ws yet, because the bonds=C2=A0<em>are</em><em>=C2=A0</em>insurance against=
 miscellaneous bad stuff, and Credit Suisse sure did get up to a lot of tha=
t.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0"=
 cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
